WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.329 --> 00:00:06.410
- Hello, everyone
and welcome back.

00:00:06.410 --> 00:00:07.750
My name is Yukio Lippit.

00:00:07.750 --> 00:00:09.730
I am the Faculty
Director of the Arts

00:00:09.730 --> 00:00:12.130
at the Radcliffe Institute,
and a co-organizer

00:00:12.130 --> 00:00:16.149
of this conference, which is
titled Game Changers: Sports,

00:00:16.149 --> 00:00:18.160
Gender, and society.

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:20.230
I'd like to offer just
a few brief comments.

00:00:20.230 --> 00:00:22.730
Before introducing our
next two speakers--

00:00:22.730 --> 00:00:26.140
the conference keynote speaker
Leila Ali in conversation

00:00:26.140 --> 00:00:28.900
with our moderator
Christine Brennan.

00:00:28.900 --> 00:00:30.910
Now we trust that
by now if you've

00:00:30.910 --> 00:00:32.930
been following the
conference you share

00:00:32.930 --> 00:00:35.830
the conviction of the
organizers that the relationship

00:00:35.830 --> 00:00:39.760
between sports, and gender,
and society is complex and ever

00:00:39.760 --> 00:00:42.490
evolving, and that now
seems to be a particularly

00:00:42.490 --> 00:00:46.030
opportune moment to
reflect upon and re-examine

00:00:46.030 --> 00:00:48.220
its many dimensions.

00:00:48.220 --> 00:00:50.230
This morning, we
heard a panel that

00:00:50.230 --> 00:00:54.430
did so from a historical
perspective, framed, of course,

00:00:54.430 --> 00:00:58.240
through a consideration of
the consequences of Title IX,

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:01.060
and what it means for athletic
participation and gender

00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:02.530
equality.

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:05.379
This panel included a
really beautiful meditation

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:09.250
on this idea of sports
as a birthright--

00:01:09.250 --> 00:01:10.840
as somehow a
fundamental part of what

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:14.530
it means to be human, of
sports as a basic part

00:01:14.530 --> 00:01:17.110
of the human experience,
and the challenges

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:20.060
that have faced women and
people with disabilities

00:01:20.060 --> 00:01:21.880
in staking a claim to it.

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:25.360
We also heard in the late
morning in the panel on Gender

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:31.120
and Wellness of a host of
perspectives on this issue from

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:36.190
the NCAA perspective, from
the US anti-doping agency,

00:01:36.190 --> 00:01:39.214
and community sports, and
how to think about gender--

00:01:39.214 --> 00:01:40.630
the issue of gender
and difference

00:01:40.630 --> 00:01:42.700
in sports from
myriad perspectives--

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:46.300
neurophysiological,
biomechanical.

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:49.390
From the perspective of the--

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:52.180
from legal, cultural, social.

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:54.700
We also learned why the
Scandinavian countries

00:01:54.700 --> 00:01:56.980
are the happiest in the world.

00:02:01.340 --> 00:02:03.840
Later this afternoon, we'll be
exploring yet a different set

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:07.620
of issues in the panel Gender,
Media, and Popular Culture.

00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:09.300
It goes without saying
that we have now

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:12.030
been living in a saturated
media culture for some time

00:02:12.030 --> 00:02:14.460
now from that
moment that was so,

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:18.360
I think, well captured
in the movie Anchorman 2

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:20.970
when Ron Burgundy,
played by Will Ferrell,

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:22.860
is being recruited
during the 1980s

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:27.930
by an executive for a new
24-hour news channel, GNN.

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:30.240
And blurts out, that
is without doubt,

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:33.382
the dumbest thing
I've ever heard.

00:02:33.382 --> 00:02:35.340
You might say that the
afternoon panel examines

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:38.970
what happens in the wake
of the emergence of GNN,

00:02:38.970 --> 00:02:41.760
and more generally of sports
through the culture of sports,

00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:43.530
the fandoms, the
media practices,

00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:45.750
and the popular culture
with which sports

00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:48.070
have become so imbricated.

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:50.190
Now as a conference
organizer, I can

00:02:50.190 --> 00:02:51.900
tell you that the
Radcliffe institute is

00:02:51.900 --> 00:02:55.320
this interesting place where the
faculty directors get together

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:58.860
with the dean and administrators
and propose conference themes.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:03.870
Then, we propose an absolutely
improbable dream list of world

00:03:03.870 --> 00:03:05.147
experts to address them.

00:03:05.147 --> 00:03:07.230
And then we go out and ask
them, and they say yes,

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:09.150
and here we are.

00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:10.627
Amazing.

00:03:10.627 --> 00:03:12.210
And nowhere is this
more the case than

00:03:12.210 --> 00:03:15.420
with our keynote
speaker, Laila Ali.

00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:16.950
She needs no introduction.

00:03:16.950 --> 00:03:18.990
And you will find in
our conference booklets

00:03:18.990 --> 00:03:22.500
an extensive bio for her,
as with all of our speakers.

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:25.230
But let me just say that
in a remarkably wide

00:03:25.230 --> 00:03:28.290
ranging achievements and
experiences as a boxing

00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:32.400
champion and world class
athlete, actress, commentator,

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:34.680
and past president of the
nonprofit Women's Sports

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:37.950
Foundation, Laila Ali
has lived or embodied

00:03:37.950 --> 00:03:40.740
in one form or another
many of the issues that we

00:03:40.740 --> 00:03:43.290
are addressing in
today's conference.

00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:45.660
She is an advocate
for equality for women

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:47.160
in the world of
professional sports

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:49.484
who is both powerful
and thoughtful.

00:03:49.484 --> 00:03:51.150
Someone who will be
able to offer unique

00:03:51.150 --> 00:03:52.740
perspectives on
the many questions

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:55.860
that emerge at the intersection
of sport and gender.

00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:58.440
And we are absolutely delighted
and privileged to have her

00:03:58.440 --> 00:03:59.580
here.

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:02.310
And it was a tall order to
find an interlocutor who

00:04:02.310 --> 00:04:04.980
could activate to the fullest
this opportunity for engagement

00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:07.380
with Laila Ali,
but we have somehow

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:09.030
found the ideal person--

00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:11.430
Christine Brennan, an award
winning national sports

00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:14.340
columnist and best selling
author whose pioneering status

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:16.890
in sports journalism offers
her equally unique insights

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:19.980
into the issues we've been
addressing throughout the day.

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:23.830
And she has just flown in from
a blustery day in Augusta,

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:26.550
Georgia, covering the
Masters to be here with us,

00:04:26.550 --> 00:04:29.670
and it's a real honor to be
able to have her join us today.

00:04:29.670 --> 00:04:31.380
And before welcoming
them to the stage,

00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:33.750
let me explain how
this will proceed.

00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:35.910
After Laila Ali and
Christine Brennan

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:38.520
conclude their conversation,
we will take questions

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:39.720
from the audience.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:41.700
A mic will be placed
in the central aisle,

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:43.440
and we ask that you
come up to the mic,

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:46.410
introduce yourself before
asking your question.

00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:49.416
Now I'm just going to linger
here for just a few seconds

00:04:49.416 --> 00:04:50.790
because I'm pretty
sure that this

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:52.380
is the only time
in my life that I'm

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:55.890
going to be able to
introduce a world renowned,

00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:57.135
undefeated boxing champion.

00:05:00.470 --> 00:05:02.090
Without further
ado, please join me

00:05:02.090 --> 00:05:05.740
in welcoming Laila Ali and
Christine Brennan to the stage.

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:12.110
- Thank you.

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:19.100
- Wow.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:19.790
Is my mic on?

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:20.290
Yes.

00:05:20.290 --> 00:05:22.160
How are you doing?

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:23.600
I'm really excited to be here.

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:24.410
Honored to be here.

00:05:24.410 --> 00:05:27.590
I've already learned
a couple new words--

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:29.490
words I need to go
look up, thank you.

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:33.320
But thank you so much to Dean
Elizabeth Cohen for inviting

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:35.210
me, and like I said,
I'm honored to be here,

00:05:35.210 --> 00:05:37.400
share my story with you.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:40.832
Looking forward to
discussing my story with you.

00:05:40.832 --> 00:05:43.040
I just want to start by
saying that I think all of us

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.820
know that now more than
ever, we're living in a time

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:50.270
where women, especially,
need to be inspired

00:05:50.270 --> 00:05:54.722
to find that greatness within
themselves that we all have.

00:05:54.722 --> 00:05:55.930
I think that we're champions.

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:56.630
We're warriors.

00:05:56.630 --> 00:05:57.890
We're definitely athletes.

00:05:57.890 --> 00:05:59.270
We know that.

00:05:59.270 --> 00:06:00.620
That's what I love about sports.

00:06:00.620 --> 00:06:03.860
I love that sports can
be a vehicle for us

00:06:03.860 --> 00:06:06.890
as women to find all of
those leadership qualities

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:08.510
that are there.

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:10.910
One of the biggest
regrets that I have--

00:06:10.910 --> 00:06:14.480
I have very few, aside
from some of the guys maybe

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:17.540
in the past I've dated,
but one of the biggest

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:20.870
regrets that I have is that I
didn't play sports growing up.

00:06:20.870 --> 00:06:23.180
A lot of people
assumed that I did.

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:27.154
They also assume that I got
into boxing because my father is

00:06:27.154 --> 00:06:28.820
the greatest of all
time, but I actually

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:31.100
didn't want to
box myself until I

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:34.169
saw women boxing on
television for the first time.

00:06:34.169 --> 00:06:36.210
And I remember that moment
like it was yesterday.

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:40.490
I was in complete awe, and
wanted to do it myself,

00:06:40.490 --> 00:06:43.910
so I think of that now
as me being an athlete

00:06:43.910 --> 00:06:46.550
and a role model to
other girls growing up.

00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:49.770
Not even necessarily to want
to become a boxer, but just

00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:53.690
expanding our minds of
what's possible for us to do.

00:06:53.690 --> 00:06:57.560
So, again, I'm honored to
speak to you all here today,

00:06:57.560 --> 00:07:00.710
and I would love to go through
that story with you guys.

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:01.570
- All right.

00:07:01.570 --> 00:07:04.310
Well, what a great
opening statement.

00:07:04.310 --> 00:07:06.694
And I was saying-- we were
just in the green room--

00:07:06.694 --> 00:07:09.110
I was saying, you know that
thing, the school yard thing--

00:07:09.110 --> 00:07:10.925
like, my, dad can take your dad.

00:07:15.850 --> 00:07:18.870
That wasn't so good.

00:07:18.870 --> 00:07:20.650
Maybe my mom could
take your mom.

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:22.200
- Probably not that either.

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:24.120
I'm just joking.

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:25.250
My mom's a little feisty.

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:26.960
- My mom was too.

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:27.460
OK.

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:27.959
I'm 0 for 2.

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:32.480
You talked to your dad.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:35.110
And when we were
chatting a few days ago

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:36.970
just to kind of prepare
for this, and what

00:07:36.970 --> 00:07:40.410
a wonderful scene this is to
see all of you in this gym,

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:43.210
in this historic setting.

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:45.340
The old boys' club of
Augusta National or here?

00:07:45.340 --> 00:07:46.673
I think I should just stay here.

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:50.640
All right.

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.427
I'll stay.

00:07:52.427 --> 00:07:54.010
But we were talking,
and I said, is it

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:55.134
OK you talk about your dad?

00:07:55.134 --> 00:07:56.710
And you said, of course.

00:07:56.710 --> 00:07:58.870
And there's so many
ways we could go

00:07:58.870 --> 00:08:00.430
with the greatest of all time--

00:08:00.430 --> 00:08:03.310
Mohammad Ali-- but you
just touched upon it.

00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:06.310
So you did not really play--
you didn't play sports.

00:08:06.310 --> 00:08:07.810
You didn't think
you'd be a boxer,

00:08:07.810 --> 00:08:10.420
and as I recall, your dad
was not exactly thrilled

00:08:10.420 --> 00:08:12.737
when you said, hey dad,
I want to be a boxer.

00:08:12.737 --> 00:08:14.320
Why don't you tell
everyone that story

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:15.694
because I think
it's illustrative

00:08:15.694 --> 00:08:18.310
of not only, of course,
your personal story,

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:21.460
but also of a girl trying
to say to a dad, hey,

00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:24.250
I want to play sports, and the
dad kind of being reluctant,

00:08:24.250 --> 00:08:27.310
and then obviously
finally coming around.

00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:28.000
Right?

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:29.980
- Well for me.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:32.830
I'm not just any girl, and
it wasn't just any dad.

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:36.370
This is Muhammad Ali, the
greatest of all times.

00:08:36.370 --> 00:08:40.893
He has his youngest
daughter now wanting to box.

00:08:40.893 --> 00:08:42.309
So he didn't have
any of his kids.

00:08:42.309 --> 00:08:46.537
I don't think he wanted
any of his kids to box.

00:08:46.537 --> 00:08:48.370
We can go into that
later, but as a fighter,

00:08:48.370 --> 00:08:49.850
I wouldn't want my
kids to box, either.

00:08:49.850 --> 00:08:51.224
So it's just one
of those things.

00:08:51.224 --> 00:08:53.840
But for me, I
decided that I want

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:57.040
to start training after I saw
women's boxing on television.

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:01.030
And I was in school full
time, and I had a business--

00:09:01.030 --> 00:09:02.560
I had a nail salon
because I started

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:05.110
going to school to learn how
to do nails when I was 16.

00:09:05.110 --> 00:09:08.200
And I built up my clientele,
saved up my money,

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:09.670
I was subleasing.

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:11.592
And I had this whole
plan, and I'm a planner.

00:09:11.592 --> 00:09:13.300
So I was like, I'm
going to go to school,

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:15.430
I'm going to live on
my own, which I did.

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:18.245
And I'm going to focus on
building this business.

00:09:18.245 --> 00:09:20.120
And then all of a sudden
I see women's boxing

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:22.655
and I'm like within myself--

00:09:22.655 --> 00:09:23.530
- How did you see it.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:24.321
You watch it on TV.

00:09:24.321 --> 00:09:27.901
- I turned on television to
watch a Mike Tyson fight,

00:09:27.901 --> 00:09:30.400
and I wasn't a big boxing fan,
but I watched the big fights,

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.530
and then here come these women
into the ring on the under

00:09:32.530 --> 00:09:33.010
card.

00:09:33.010 --> 00:09:35.093
So I think that was the
first time a lot of people

00:09:35.093 --> 00:09:39.040
saw women's boxing, and
that moment-- that's when

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:40.780
the seed was planted within me.

00:09:40.780 --> 00:09:42.490
And I remember saying,
I want to do that.

00:09:42.490 --> 00:09:45.700
And I was with my best friend
and her father, he said Laila,

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:47.200
those women will
take your head off.

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:48.610
And I was like, no, I can do it.

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:49.110
I can do it.

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:51.820
But then when I went home,
and the fear and the doubt

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:54.960
started to set in, and I don't
know if I'd be able to do it,

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:56.721
meaning change my plans.

00:09:56.721 --> 00:09:57.970
You know, I've told everybody.

00:09:57.970 --> 00:09:59.936
I've said this is
my plan, and then

00:09:59.936 --> 00:10:01.060
what are they going to say?

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:01.930
What are they going to think?

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:02.638
Just all of that.

00:10:02.638 --> 00:10:04.240
I was a young girl.

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:06.470
But that feeling
did not go away,

00:10:06.470 --> 00:10:08.940
so I thought about it
for I think about a year.

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:11.500
I'm really bad with timelines,
but it took us about a year.

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:12.620
And then I decided,
you know what,

00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:14.770
I'm going to go find a
trainer and start training.

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:15.940
And I did it all on my own.

00:10:15.940 --> 00:10:17.185
I didn't ask my dad for help.

00:10:17.185 --> 00:10:19.810
I was still trying to figure out
if it was something I actually

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:21.594
wanted to do-- if I
had the talent to do,

00:10:21.594 --> 00:10:24.010
because I knew I was going to
be successful with this nail

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:26.050
business and become
an entrepreneur,

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:27.850
and boxing was so new for me.

00:10:27.850 --> 00:10:29.890
So I went to the gym,
started training,

00:10:29.890 --> 00:10:33.070
and at a certain point my
father found out about it,

00:10:33.070 --> 00:10:34.892
and I had already
decided that yes, I

00:10:34.892 --> 00:10:36.100
was, in fact, going to do it.

00:10:36.100 --> 00:10:38.036
And that's when he asked me--

00:10:38.036 --> 00:10:40.660
came in town, because he didn't
live in Los Angeles-- and said,

00:10:40.660 --> 00:10:42.010
you know, I hear
that you're boxing,

00:10:42.010 --> 00:10:43.468
and you're going
to start fighting.

00:10:43.468 --> 00:10:44.570
I was like, yeah I am.

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:47.597
He basically tried to talk
me out of it indirectly.

00:10:47.597 --> 00:10:49.930
That's how my father-- he
brings up every negative thing

00:10:49.930 --> 00:10:51.220
that he possibly can.

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:53.249
What happens if you
get knocked out?

00:10:53.249 --> 00:10:54.790
What happens if you
get knocked down?

00:10:54.790 --> 00:10:56.230
The whole world's going
to be watching you,

00:10:56.230 --> 00:10:57.420
and all my answers
was based on-- well,

00:10:57.420 --> 00:10:59.470
when you got knocked
down, you got back up.

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:01.240
I don't think I want to get
knocked out, but if I do,

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:02.220
I'm going to ask for a rematch.

00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:03.678
You know, I gave
all these answers,

00:11:03.678 --> 00:11:05.050
like what else could he say?

00:11:05.050 --> 00:11:07.050
And he knew he was
talking to Laila,

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:10.480
