It's just what you
take from sports

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:53.990
that can help you in so many
different areas of your life.

00:31:53.990 --> 00:31:56.060
Your kids got to know
their grandfather.

00:31:56.060 --> 00:31:56.900
- Oh yeah.

00:31:56.900 --> 00:31:59.810
And they knew, but that they
didn't really understand.

00:31:59.810 --> 00:32:01.935
Just like when I was a kid,
people always asked me,

00:32:01.935 --> 00:32:04.371
when did you first learn
how great your father was,

00:32:04.371 --> 00:32:05.370
or why people loved him?

00:32:05.370 --> 00:32:07.910
And I can't even really
remember the moment,

00:32:07.910 --> 00:32:10.460
but when I was eight or nine,
you don't really understand.

00:32:10.460 --> 00:32:12.030
You understand people
are coming up to you,

00:32:12.030 --> 00:32:13.320
everywhere you go
there's a crowd.

00:32:13.320 --> 00:32:14.480
It's kind of annoying
because you're

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:16.271
standing around waiting
for a couple hours.

00:32:16.271 --> 00:32:18.480
You get stuck everywhere.

00:32:18.480 --> 00:32:21.680
I never wanted to go anywhere
with my dad because I knew--

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:24.832
he loved doing magic tricks
and drawing in a crowd.

00:32:24.832 --> 00:32:27.290
So you're going to be there
for two or three hours watching

00:32:27.290 --> 00:32:30.529
those same magic tricks.

00:32:30.529 --> 00:32:32.320
- Did you ever figure
out the magic tricks?

00:32:32.320 --> 00:32:33.150
- Oh yeah.

00:32:33.150 --> 00:32:33.650
Oh my God.

00:32:33.650 --> 00:32:40.820
He had this one where he would
pretend that this handkerchief

00:32:40.820 --> 00:32:41.900
would disappear.

00:32:41.900 --> 00:32:44.150
So he had a plastic thumb.

00:32:44.150 --> 00:32:47.090
So he'd have the thumb, and he'd
say, here's the handkerchief.

00:32:47.090 --> 00:32:49.240
And then he'd take
the thumb off,

00:32:49.240 --> 00:32:50.990
and stuff the handkerchief
into the thumb,

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:52.320
and then put it back on.

00:32:52.320 --> 00:32:54.200
So I saw that and
he'd say, oh, and then

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:57.020
as he got older and
got sick, the thumb

00:32:57.020 --> 00:32:58.340
would be the wrong color.

00:32:58.340 --> 00:33:01.620
He would have a
white person's thumb.

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:02.990
I like dad.

00:33:02.990 --> 00:33:05.576
People could see it,
but they were still--

00:33:05.576 --> 00:33:07.910
then he had this
levitating one that he

00:33:07.910 --> 00:33:09.560
did where he'd act
like he was floating

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:11.030
and he really was
on his front toes.

00:33:11.030 --> 00:33:12.238
So, like, I knew all of them.

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:17.060
As a child, you're just
like, oh, this is so corny.

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:20.690
But he would also pass out his
pamphlets, and he was still--

00:33:20.690 --> 00:33:22.040
about Islam.

00:33:22.040 --> 00:33:23.820
So he would write his signature.

00:33:23.820 --> 00:33:25.700
And he spent hours
writing his signature

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:28.520
so that he could pass them out
to people as he met people.

00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:31.505
So I saw this all the time.

00:33:31.505 --> 00:33:34.700
And I get it now, but
as a kid I didn't ever

00:33:34.700 --> 00:33:36.020
want to go with him.

00:33:36.020 --> 00:33:37.245
I forget the question, again.

00:33:37.245 --> 00:33:41.690
- It was about the kids
and looking up to him.

00:33:41.690 --> 00:33:42.980
Of course, you lost your dad.

00:33:42.980 --> 00:33:44.979
- Oh this is what I was
going to say, I'm sorry.

00:33:44.979 --> 00:33:50.270
So my kids knew, but it
wasn't until he passed away

00:33:50.270 --> 00:33:52.430
that they really got
the opportunity to see,

00:33:52.430 --> 00:33:54.350
because now they're
showing all these specials

00:33:54.350 --> 00:33:56.550
on my father on television.

00:33:56.550 --> 00:33:59.210
We went to his memorial
service, and they

00:33:59.210 --> 00:34:00.980
saw all these
different people come.

00:34:00.980 --> 00:34:02.780
It was very
overwhelming for them,

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:04.850
and then they went to
the Muhammad Ali center

00:34:04.850 --> 00:34:06.470
for the first time.

00:34:06.470 --> 00:34:07.520
My son is older.

00:34:07.520 --> 00:34:09.739
He's 8 now, and he's
really, really bright,

00:34:09.739 --> 00:34:12.560
smart, and he was able to
just kind of watch the videos,

00:34:12.560 --> 00:34:13.590
and see the timeline.

00:34:13.590 --> 00:34:16.070
And I was even amazed
because I know my dad.

00:34:16.070 --> 00:34:18.830
And I'm not a Muhammad Ali fan,
so I haven't read all of his

00:34:18.830 --> 00:34:21.038
books-- of the books written
about him and all that--

00:34:21.038 --> 00:34:25.040
but to be at the Ali center
and just see this long wall--

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:27.260
this timeline of all
these important dates,

00:34:27.260 --> 00:34:29.750
and all of the things that
he's done in his life.

00:34:29.750 --> 00:34:33.889
Because I never took the
time to really go through.

00:34:33.889 --> 00:34:35.120
It was amazing to me.

00:34:35.120 --> 00:34:38.510
And for them to see that, and
see all those wonderful people

00:34:38.510 --> 00:34:40.010
get on the stage
and talk about him.

00:34:40.010 --> 00:34:43.040
Then I could tell that when
they started to kind of get it.

00:34:43.040 --> 00:34:45.677
And my daughter had this
really special connection--

00:34:45.677 --> 00:34:47.510
like a spiritual
connection with my father--

00:34:47.510 --> 00:34:49.250
ever since she was a baby.

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:52.520
- My father didn't really
speak that much anymore,

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:56.420
and towards the end, he
was in a hospital bed.

00:34:56.420 --> 00:34:59.960
He was on a feeding
tube and all that.

00:34:59.960 --> 00:35:03.650
And my daughter-- most
people-- or kids--

00:35:03.650 --> 00:35:05.060
were afraid because
he's shaking,

00:35:05.060 --> 00:35:07.535
he's got really big
hands, and my daughter,

00:35:07.535 --> 00:35:09.660
since she was a baby would
just go right up to him,

00:35:09.660 --> 00:35:12.380
hug him, and she'd kiss him,
and then she'd just kind of

00:35:12.380 --> 00:35:14.420
get into the bed with him.

00:35:14.420 --> 00:35:15.462
She'd run back and forth.

00:35:15.462 --> 00:35:17.920
Every five minutes she'd go
back and visit him and kiss him

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:20.270
and his eyes would just light
up because he loves kids.

00:35:20.270 --> 00:35:21.530
He loves giving kisses.

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:25.520
And for her not to
be afraid of him--

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:26.934
so it was amazing.

00:35:26.934 --> 00:35:28.850
It was amazing to see
the connection they had.

00:35:28.850 --> 00:35:31.252
That has been the hardest
thing for me is Sidney.

00:35:31.252 --> 00:35:32.210
She doesn't understand.

00:35:32.210 --> 00:35:33.620
Why did poppa have to leave?

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:36.410
Why did he have to go to heaven?

00:35:36.410 --> 00:35:39.260
She's talking about him
still at least twice a week.

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:42.950
So she knows, but she doesn't
really understand why.

00:35:42.950 --> 00:35:46.310
So it's going to be interesting
to see as they get older when

00:35:46.310 --> 00:35:49.910
they really understand and
hear the stories of who

00:35:49.910 --> 00:35:50.971
he was as a human being.

00:35:50.971 --> 00:35:52.970
And I think they're going
to be even more proud.

00:35:52.970 --> 00:35:54.560
But my son looks just like him.

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:56.450
So my son opened a
book the other day,

00:35:56.450 --> 00:35:58.580
and was like, that
looks like me.

00:35:58.580 --> 00:35:59.810
I'm like, I know.

00:35:59.810 --> 00:36:01.250
When he was 12--

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:03.749
we've been telling him, you
look just like your grandfather.

00:36:03.749 --> 00:36:05.550
And I love it because
I'm the youngest.

00:36:05.550 --> 00:36:08.420
My dad has 13
grandkids, but my child

00:36:08.420 --> 00:36:10.100
is the only one
that looks like him.

00:36:10.100 --> 00:36:13.090
So I'm like, yeah.

00:36:13.090 --> 00:36:13.610
- Good work.

00:36:13.610 --> 00:36:14.710
Good work on that.

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:17.240
When we were
talking and chatting

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:18.740
about what we wanted
to talk about,

00:36:18.740 --> 00:36:20.660
I mentioned the 1996 Olympics.

00:36:20.660 --> 00:36:23.860
And I think because
for so many of us

00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:26.720
it is that iconic
moment for your dad.

00:36:26.720 --> 00:36:29.660
Those of us who didn't
really know him in his prime.

00:36:29.660 --> 00:36:33.210
Obviously-- I remember
those Ali-Frazier fights,

00:36:33.210 --> 00:36:35.360
but I was little, and
you weren't born yet.

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:37.970
But I was at the 1996
Olympics in Atlanta,

00:36:37.970 --> 00:36:40.240
and I'm sure all of you
remember this moment,

00:36:40.240 --> 00:36:43.250
but no one knew who was
going to light the torch.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:44.930
And this is the US Olympics.

00:36:44.930 --> 00:36:46.694
You figure it's going
to be a US athlete.

00:36:46.694 --> 00:36:48.110
And lots of names
were thrown out.

00:36:48.110 --> 00:36:49.818
But I don't even
remember your dad's name

00:36:49.818 --> 00:36:52.310
being thrown out that much.

00:36:52.310 --> 00:36:54.710
Michael Jordan,
all kinds of names.

00:36:54.710 --> 00:36:56.134
So now comes the moment.

00:36:56.134 --> 00:36:58.550
I'll set it up, but I want to
hear what you were thinking.

00:36:58.550 --> 00:37:02.040
So now we're in the stadium,
opening ceremonies, 80,000

00:37:02.040 --> 00:37:02.540
people.

00:37:02.540 --> 00:37:05.906
It's dark and the torch is
going around, and Janet Evans--

00:37:05.906 --> 00:37:08.280
of course, you remember Janet
Evans, the Olympic swimmer.

00:37:08.280 --> 00:37:11.240
Now she's taking it up
to near where you're

00:37:11.240 --> 00:37:13.550
going to light the cauldron,
and we're thinking, well,

00:37:13.550 --> 00:37:16.970
it's Janet Evans, which is
not insignificant, and would

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:19.520
have been very well deserved--

00:37:19.520 --> 00:37:22.580
Olympic gold medalist, and
a great Olympic champion,

00:37:22.580 --> 00:37:24.350
a great athlete.

00:37:24.350 --> 00:37:29.630
And then out of the
darkness emerges your dad.

00:37:29.630 --> 00:37:31.850
And my last words
on this because

00:37:31.850 --> 00:37:33.140
this is all your story--

00:37:33.140 --> 00:37:35.840
my last words, though, as I'm
a journalist sitting there,

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:37.790
and we're all
there, I have never

00:37:37.790 --> 00:37:43.040
heard 80,000 people
gasp in unison.

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:44.150
And it wasn't just me.

00:37:44.150 --> 00:37:46.280
Bob Costas and I were
talking recently,

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:47.670
for a column about him.

00:37:47.670 --> 00:37:49.670
And I said, what's your
favorite Olympic moment?

00:37:49.670 --> 00:37:51.760
He's covered a lot
of them, as I have.

00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:54.500
Mohammad Ali lighting the
torch is his favorite moment.

00:37:54.500 --> 00:37:55.910
And he said the
same exact thing.

00:37:55.910 --> 00:37:58.940
That audible gasp of like
the air being sucked out

00:37:58.940 --> 00:38:01.460
of this outdoor
stadium as Muhammad Ali

00:38:01.460 --> 00:38:04.210
emerged to light the torch.

00:38:04.210 --> 00:38:05.450
- It was the same for me.

00:38:05.450 --> 00:38:08.960
I mean we did not know we didn't
know our whole family didn't

00:38:08.960 --> 00:38:10.190
know they kept such a secret.

00:38:10.190 --> 00:38:11.870
You know it is-- if
you tell one person,

00:38:11.870 --> 00:38:13.635
it might get to the other.

00:38:13.635 --> 00:38:14.510
Our family is so big.

00:38:14.510 --> 00:38:16.310
So we didn't even know.

00:38:16.310 --> 00:38:20.540
So for me, I was
so proud of my dad,

00:38:20.540 --> 00:38:23.030
and it just really
brought tears to my eyes.

00:38:23.030 --> 00:38:24.200
- And you were-- you
were not in the stands.

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:24.860
- I was not there.

00:38:24.860 --> 00:38:25.520
I wasn't there.

00:38:25.520 --> 00:38:27.140
I was watching on television.

00:38:27.140 --> 00:38:32.025
And I didn't know, so luckily
I saw it and caught it.

00:38:32.025 --> 00:38:33.400
Sometimes you miss
those moments.

00:38:33.400 --> 00:38:34.240
- How funny would
that have been?

00:38:34.240 --> 00:38:36.281
Someone calls you, say,
hey were you watching TV?

00:38:36.281 --> 00:38:37.340
No.

00:38:37.340 --> 00:38:38.830
- Yeah, so that's me.

00:38:38.830 --> 00:38:42.135
I'm that person that
would miss something.

00:38:42.135 --> 00:38:43.760
It really just brought
tears to my eyes

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:47.730
because my father's never
hid the fact that he's sick.

00:38:47.730 --> 00:38:50.240
He said that boxing was
going to be his platform

00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:53.360
to do his humanitarian
work, and we already

00:38:53.360 --> 00:38:56.281
know that he had an ego,
and he was conceited,

00:38:56.281 --> 00:38:58.280
and he had a lot of pride,
and all those things,

00:38:58.280 --> 00:39:01.730
but not so much that he
wouldn't get out and be

00:39:01.730 --> 00:39:05.194
a symbol for other
people who had illnesses.

00:39:05.194 --> 00:39:07.610
And he was still standing there
strong, even with his hand

00:39:07.610 --> 00:39:10.280
shaking, and so I was
just proud of him.

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:14.570
Because he's such a sweetie pie.

00:39:14.570 --> 00:39:17.210
That's the first thing I think
of when I think about my father

00:39:17.210 --> 00:39:19.810
outside of just who he is
as a man, as an athlete,

00:39:19.810 --> 00:39:23.660
is just how sweet and
gentle he is as a person.

00:39:23.660 --> 00:39:25.280
So it just brought
tears to my eyes.

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:27.867
I don't really have a big
story other than that.

00:39:27.867 --> 00:39:28.700
- That's a good one.

00:39:28.700 --> 00:39:29.658
That's one of the best.

00:39:29.658 --> 00:39:32.780
And will be, of course, iconic,
and the video is iconic,

00:39:32.780 --> 00:39:35.610
and we saw it, of course, so
often when he passed away.

00:39:35.610 --> 00:39:39.841
And, of course, our condolences
to you and your family on that.

00:39:39.841 --> 00:39:41.090
Should we start the questions?

00:39:41.090 --> 00:39:41.640
You want to do that?

00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:42.140
- Why not?

00:39:42.140 --> 00:39:42.710
Sure.

00:39:42.710 --> 00:39:43.640
- We've got--

00:39:43.640 --> 00:39:46.150
I believe we've got the
microphone here in the middle.

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:49.829
We'd love to hear your
questions and fire away.

00:39:49.829 --> 00:39:52.370
Why don't you tell us who you
are and then ask your question.

00:39:52.370 --> 00:39:52.910
Thank you.

00:39:52.910 --> 00:39:53.410
- Sure.

00:39:53.410 --> 00:39:56.060
Hi, I'm Sammy Nagy Chao,
I'm a master's student

00:39:56.060 --> 00:39:58.580
at the Harvard Graduate
School of Education,

00:39:58.580 --> 00:40:02.150
and I have a real interest
in developing positive body

00:40:02.150 --> 00:40:07.350
images in my students, whether
I'm coaching them or teaching.

00:40:07.350 --> 00:40:09.290
So I just wanted
to get any thoughts

00:40:09.290 --> 00:40:11.900
that you have on
developing positive body

00:40:11.900 --> 00:40:14.960
images in all genders,
and especially

00:40:14.960 --> 00:40:20.690
challenging a lot of ascetic
sports ideal body images.

00:40:20.690 --> 00:40:26.150
- Well, for me I don't
have the ideal body

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:29.570
you would think as far as a
lot of women are concerned,

00:40:29.570 --> 00:40:30.260
in general.

00:40:30.260 --> 00:40:32.057
Because I'm a big girl.

00:40:32.057 --> 00:40:34.640
A lot of times we're concerned
about our weight, and our size,

00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:35.181
and all that.

00:40:35.181 --> 00:40:37.310
I weighed 168 pounds
when I was fighting.

00:40:37.310 --> 00:40:40.130
I weigh 190 pounds right now.

00:40:40.130 --> 00:40:42.890
So that's the first thing a
lot of people are surprised at.

00:40:42.890 --> 00:40:45.800
And I have no problem
saying it, because that's

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:46.850
one thing that I do.

00:40:46.850 --> 00:40:48.770
I talk about it
openly just for people

00:40:48.770 --> 00:40:51.103
to see that it doesn't really
matter how much you weigh.

00:40:51.103 --> 00:40:53.390
It's really about how you feel.

00:40:53.390 --> 00:40:56.210
And I try to focus
more on being healthy,

00:40:56.210 --> 00:40:59.592
opposed to being
a certain size--

00:40:59.592 --> 00:41:02.870
with eating right,
with working out

00:41:02.870 --> 00:41:05.330
comes the benefit
of looking good.

00:41:05.330 --> 00:41:07.730
So when you focus on that
then everything else kind of

00:41:07.730 --> 00:41:08.720
falls into place.

00:41:08.720 --> 00:41:10.261
And I think it really
just comes down

00:41:10.261 --> 00:41:14.110
to understanding that we're
all special, we're all unique,

00:41:14.110 --> 00:41:16.195
and that God created us
exactly the way that we're

00:41:16.195 --> 00:41:16.820
supposed to be.

00:41:16.820 --> 00:41:18.319
That's the first
foundation that you

00:41:18.319 --> 00:41:20.474
have to have, and
stop looking at others

00:41:20.474 --> 00:41:21.890
and wishing you
had what they had.

00:41:21.890 --> 00:41:23.467
Because nobody's perfect.

00:41:23.467 --> 00:41:26.050
A lot of people may look at me,
and think, oh, you're so this,

00:41:26.050 --> 00:41:26.900
you're so that.

00:41:26.900 --> 00:41:29.525
I can tell you, look, there are
things that if I could change--

00:41:29.525 --> 00:41:32.150
the fact that I
wear size 12 shoe--

00:41:32.150 --> 00:41:34.140
that right there,
I don't really care

00:41:34.140 --> 00:41:36.320
that my feet are a size
12, the problem with it

00:41:36.320 --> 00:41:39.200
is it's hard to find shoes.

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:42.207
So I have to order shoes
online, and I'm, ah.

00:41:42.207 --> 00:41:43.040
So that's the thing.

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:44.440
But it's not because it's,
like, I'm embarrassed

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:45.440
because my feet are big.

00:41:45.440 --> 00:41:46.250
They fit my body.

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:47.660
You know, and when
I was younger,

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:49.160
I was like, why are
my hands so big?

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:50.390
I got big hands.

00:41:50.390 --> 00:41:52.670
You know, and it's hard
for me to find jewelry.

00:41:52.670 --> 00:41:54.503
But then when I started
knocking people out,

00:41:54.503 --> 00:41:55.477
I was like, thank you.

00:41:59.293 --> 00:42:02.240
That's why.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:04.410
Like I said, it's
just everything

00:42:04.410 --> 00:42:07.650
is a way that is for a reason.

00:42:07.650 --> 00:42:10.050
But, again, I don't have
the perfect answer for you,

00:42:10.050 --> 00:42:11.950
but I think that
with a lot of girls,

00:42:11.950 --> 00:42:15.180
they need to understand
when you see certain images,

00:42:15.180 --> 00:42:17.124
