00:52:25.890 --> 00:52:27.780
of Radcliffe College.

00:52:27.780 --> 00:52:30.330
And when I was here, I had the
chance to hear your father.

00:52:30.330 --> 00:52:34.230
He came to speak, and he was
brilliant-- read his poetry,

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:37.220
and it's a very special memory.

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:38.310
But I had a question.

00:52:38.310 --> 00:52:42.210
I would be fascinated to
hear what was involved

00:52:42.210 --> 00:52:45.150
in training to become a boxer.

00:52:45.150 --> 00:52:46.260
Because I have--

00:52:46.260 --> 00:52:47.130
- Yes.

00:52:47.130 --> 00:52:48.020
- Very little idea.

00:52:48.020 --> 00:52:49.830
- Yes, I'll tell you.

00:52:49.830 --> 00:52:52.410
So before I started
boxing-- like I said,

00:52:52.410 --> 00:52:53.330
I didn't play sports.

00:52:53.330 --> 00:52:55.020
I wasn't in shape at all.

00:52:55.020 --> 00:52:56.229
I was like any other person--

00:52:56.229 --> 00:52:57.603
I shouldn't say
any other person,

00:52:57.603 --> 00:52:59.130
but I was like most young kids.

00:52:59.130 --> 00:53:00.300
I ate what I wanted to eat.

00:53:00.300 --> 00:53:02.091
I didn't have a gym
membership or anything.

00:53:02.091 --> 00:53:05.550
At that time I was
about 17 and 1/2.

00:53:05.550 --> 00:53:08.504
So I went down to the boxing
gym, got with a trainer,

00:53:08.504 --> 00:53:10.920
and they say, well, you've got
to come to the gym six days

00:53:10.920 --> 00:53:12.570
a week.

00:53:12.570 --> 00:53:14.280
And what I would do
when I got to the gym

00:53:14.280 --> 00:53:17.070
is I would hit the heavy bag.

00:53:17.070 --> 00:53:19.320
You know what a heavy bag is?

00:53:19.320 --> 00:53:21.570
I would hit the speed bag.

00:53:21.570 --> 00:53:24.390
There's a double in bag
to work on your eyes,

00:53:24.390 --> 00:53:26.644
jump roping, then, of
course, do your sit ups

00:53:26.644 --> 00:53:28.060
and you do all
that kind of stuff.

00:53:28.060 --> 00:53:29.518
And then you work
with your trainer

00:53:29.518 --> 00:53:30.990
on your footwork in the ring.

00:53:30.990 --> 00:53:33.790
Every fighter is different, I'll
say, but those are the basics.

00:53:33.790 --> 00:53:35.670
And you really have
to take the time

00:53:35.670 --> 00:53:38.610
to assess what your
strengths are as a fighter.

00:53:38.610 --> 00:53:41.010
So naturally, if you're tall,
and you have a long reach,

00:53:41.010 --> 00:53:43.320
you're going to work on
keeping somebody on the outside

00:53:43.320 --> 00:53:45.450
because you can hit them,
but they can't hit you.

00:53:45.450 --> 00:53:47.160
They have shorter arms.

00:53:47.160 --> 00:53:49.800
But that's not as
easy as it sounds.

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:54.517
And then for me, I
had to start running.

00:53:54.517 --> 00:53:55.350
Because I never ran.

00:53:55.350 --> 00:53:57.225
And you have to do your
roadwork as a fighter

00:53:57.225 --> 00:53:59.760
because boxing is one of
the hardest sports when

00:53:59.760 --> 00:54:03.240
it comes to endurance because,
again, you might be getting

00:54:03.240 --> 00:54:06.051
beat up, and you still
have to keep going

00:54:06.051 --> 00:54:08.550
and that takes a lot of strength
in a lot of different areas

00:54:08.550 --> 00:54:11.070
of your body, not only mentally,
but physically, as well.

00:54:11.070 --> 00:54:14.340
So learning how to run
I think was probably

00:54:14.340 --> 00:54:17.780
one of the things I
was most proud of.

00:54:17.780 --> 00:54:18.840
- How far would you run?

00:54:18.840 --> 00:54:21.640
- I started off walking running.

00:54:21.640 --> 00:54:25.590
And it's funny because my
mom has always been very fit.

00:54:25.590 --> 00:54:27.600
And she taught me how to run.

00:54:27.600 --> 00:54:29.430
So we went out and
we ran and she said,

00:54:29.430 --> 00:54:31.526
OK, we're going to
run for a minute,

00:54:31.526 --> 00:54:33.400
and then we're going to
walk for two minutes.

00:54:33.400 --> 00:54:35.250
We're going to run for a minute,
and I kind of worked my way up.

00:54:35.250 --> 00:54:36.390
And that's what
I tell people now

00:54:36.390 --> 00:54:37.530
they say they don't
know how to run.

00:54:37.530 --> 00:54:38.940
I didn't know how
to run, either.

00:54:38.940 --> 00:54:39.981
So I had to teach myself.

00:54:39.981 --> 00:54:42.270
And then I worked my
way up to four miles,

00:54:42.270 --> 00:54:44.490
because depending on
how many rounds you're

00:54:44.490 --> 00:54:46.800
fighting, when you
first start fighting,

00:54:46.800 --> 00:54:49.170
your first fight
would be four rounds.

00:54:49.170 --> 00:54:51.720
So for me, running
for miles was enough.

00:54:51.720 --> 00:54:54.220
Some fighters might say
they'll run eight miles,

00:54:54.220 --> 00:54:55.830
but you don't really need to .

00:54:55.830 --> 00:54:58.067
depending on what your
style of fighting is.

00:54:58.067 --> 00:54:58.650
But that's it.

00:54:58.650 --> 00:55:01.660
And then just every day
doing that back to back,

00:55:01.660 --> 00:55:03.750
working your way up--
a lot of shadowboxing.

00:55:03.750 --> 00:55:05.559
Just being in the
mirror, pretending

00:55:05.559 --> 00:55:07.350
there's someone in
front of you and they're

00:55:07.350 --> 00:55:08.430
throwing a certain
shot and you're

00:55:08.430 --> 00:55:09.850
getting out of the way of it.

00:55:09.850 --> 00:55:11.720
And then eventually
you start sparring,

00:55:11.720 --> 00:55:13.470
which is when you
actually get in the ring

00:55:13.470 --> 00:55:16.050
and box with other fighters.

00:55:16.050 --> 00:55:18.015
So that's always an
interesting experience

00:55:18.015 --> 00:55:20.306
to start doing that because
you're going to get beat up

00:55:20.306 --> 00:55:23.340
a little bit the first time.

00:55:23.340 --> 00:55:26.820
And I only boxed with
men, for the most part.

00:55:26.820 --> 00:55:29.030
When I first started boxing,
I boxed with some women,

00:55:29.030 --> 00:55:30.571
but it was hard to
find-- it's harder

00:55:30.571 --> 00:55:32.917
to find girls who are tall
enough and weigh enough,

00:55:32.917 --> 00:55:34.500
because boxing is
all by weight class,

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:36.210
and if you box
with a man, you've

00:55:36.210 --> 00:55:37.695
got to find a man
who is lighter,

00:55:37.695 --> 00:55:39.570
and who knows how to
work with you, who's not

00:55:39.570 --> 00:55:41.653
going to be hitting you
as hard as he possibly can

00:55:41.653 --> 00:55:44.670
because a man is always going
to be stronger than a woman.

00:55:44.670 --> 00:55:47.880
Most men, anyway.

00:55:47.880 --> 00:55:52.154
I've had some that weren't,
but anyway, it was fun.

00:55:52.154 --> 00:55:53.070
That's pretty much it.

00:55:53.070 --> 00:55:55.050
But you have to
understand the pain

00:55:55.050 --> 00:55:58.170
that your body goes through--

00:55:58.170 --> 00:56:00.255
I'm not talking about being
hit, just the next day

00:56:00.255 --> 00:56:01.380
is when you really feel it.

00:56:01.380 --> 00:56:04.617
When you're sore from
being hit, and then

00:56:04.617 --> 00:56:06.450
you have to get in there
and do it again day

00:56:06.450 --> 00:56:08.390
after day after day.

00:56:08.390 --> 00:56:09.540
It's really a mental--

00:56:09.540 --> 00:56:12.112
you have to be strong
mentally, as well,

00:56:12.112 --> 00:56:14.070
to get in there because
if you are getting hit,

00:56:14.070 --> 00:56:15.903
and you keep getting
hit with the same shot,

00:56:15.903 --> 00:56:18.990
and you're in the round, and
you can't figure out why.

00:56:18.990 --> 00:56:20.880
I'd get so mad sometimes
I would just cry.

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:22.680
I wouldn't like--
but I'd have tears

00:56:22.680 --> 00:56:25.470
because I'd be so mad
trying to figure out

00:56:25.470 --> 00:56:27.587
what I was doing wrong.

00:56:27.587 --> 00:56:28.920
But I would still keep fighting.

00:56:28.920 --> 00:56:30.045
I'd be crying and fighting.

00:56:30.045 --> 00:56:33.040
People thought I was crazy
lots of times in the gym.

00:56:33.040 --> 00:56:35.040
I may be crying, but I'm
going to keep fighting.

00:56:35.040 --> 00:56:39.630
So yeah, but it was a
grueling workout, definitely.

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:40.130
Thank you.

00:56:40.130 --> 00:56:41.520
- Thanks, [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:41.520 --> 00:56:46.040
- Hi, I'm [INAUDIBLE] from the
Ecole Polytechnique in Paris.

00:56:46.040 --> 00:56:48.630
And thank you very
much for coming.

00:56:48.630 --> 00:56:52.260
What would be the most
inspirational quote

00:56:52.260 --> 00:56:55.590
from your father you
will always remember?

00:56:55.590 --> 00:57:00.210
- I think, and I'm
going to paraphrase it.

00:57:00.210 --> 00:57:04.620
Service on earth
is the rent that I

00:57:04.620 --> 00:57:07.800
pay for my space in heaven.

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:10.200
So basically, the service
that he's doing now,

00:57:10.200 --> 00:57:13.400
he felt like was
his way into heaven.

00:57:13.400 --> 00:57:16.200
And he believed
that, by the way,

00:57:16.200 --> 00:57:17.640
which was interesting to me.

00:57:17.640 --> 00:57:20.370
Because my father was always--

00:57:20.370 --> 00:57:23.280
he believed that you've got
to do more good than you

00:57:23.280 --> 00:57:25.872
do bad to make it to heaven.

00:57:25.872 --> 00:57:28.080
I'm just thinking, wow, this
man who has done so much

00:57:28.080 --> 00:57:31.200
and changed the world, and
inspired so many lives feels

00:57:31.200 --> 00:57:33.270
like he still has
more good to do,

00:57:33.270 --> 00:57:36.000
as far as in terms of
making it to heaven.

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:40.560
But he really was all about just
giving back to other people,

00:57:40.560 --> 00:57:42.895
and he loved people.

00:57:42.895 --> 00:57:44.520
I've seen my father
just over the years

00:57:44.520 --> 00:57:48.630
get what you would think
taken advantage of by people,

00:57:48.630 --> 00:57:49.422
but he didn't care.

00:57:49.422 --> 00:57:51.838
Because if someone stole from
him or something, he's like,

00:57:51.838 --> 00:57:53.730
well he must have needed
it more than I did.

00:57:53.730 --> 00:57:57.111
And I'm just like,
that's not how I think.

00:57:57.111 --> 00:57:59.010
So we're very
different in that way.

00:57:59.010 --> 00:58:01.920
But my father is just such
a giving, loving person,

00:58:01.920 --> 00:58:03.960
and I grew up watching
my father cry.

00:58:03.960 --> 00:58:06.150
I watched that,
and that, for me,

00:58:06.150 --> 00:58:08.790
made a big difference in
who I was as an individual

00:58:08.790 --> 00:58:12.000
because seeing a man
as strong as Muhammad

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:14.190
Ali in those moments
when he's crying--

00:58:14.190 --> 00:58:17.950
not because he felt bad,
but just even out of joy

00:58:17.950 --> 00:58:18.931
or because he was sad.

00:58:18.931 --> 00:58:20.430
And he was very
sensitive and wasn't

00:58:20.430 --> 00:58:21.880
afraid to show his feelings.

00:58:21.880 --> 00:58:24.330
So that when I said he
was a male chauvinist

00:58:24.330 --> 00:58:26.940
in a certain way not
in that way, though,

00:58:26.940 --> 00:58:29.784
so that was something that I
really loved and appreciated

00:58:29.784 --> 00:58:30.450
about my father.

00:58:30.450 --> 00:58:33.090
So yes, it was all
about service to others.

00:58:33.090 --> 00:58:34.170
And he has a quote--

00:58:34.170 --> 00:58:35.629
we got to look up
that exact quote.

00:58:35.629 --> 00:58:37.045
- Maybe someone's
got their phone.

00:58:37.045 --> 00:58:37.590
- OK.

00:58:37.590 --> 00:58:38.089
- Thank you.

00:58:38.089 --> 00:58:38.760
- Thank you.

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:41.100
- And I was thinking off of
that question-- you know,

00:58:41.100 --> 00:58:45.100
your dad is so associated
with Howard Cosell,

00:58:45.100 --> 00:58:47.790
and Howard Cosell has
been gone for a long time,

00:58:47.790 --> 00:58:51.020
but I'm curious, have you ever
dealt with the Cosell family?

00:58:51.020 --> 00:58:52.590
You probably never
met Howard Cosell.

00:58:52.590 --> 00:58:53.089
- No.

00:58:53.089 --> 00:58:54.780
- But all those interviews--

00:58:54.780 --> 00:58:56.000
you guys remember those?

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:59.520
And, I'm so pretty, and
all that back and forth.

00:58:59.520 --> 00:59:01.950
I mean, your dad
obviously would have

00:59:01.950 --> 00:59:03.620
been your dad without
Howard Cosell,

00:59:03.620 --> 00:59:06.390
but I think Howard
Cosell brought out--

00:59:06.390 --> 00:59:08.921
- They had a fun relationship
for sure, the two of them

00:59:08.921 --> 00:59:09.420
together.

00:59:09.420 --> 00:59:11.753
- And there's some great
comments from those interviews,

00:59:11.753 --> 00:59:14.100
too, if you want to
look them up, for sure.

00:59:14.100 --> 00:59:14.910
Next question.

00:59:14.910 --> 00:59:17.361
- Hi my name is Ariel, and
I'm a senior at the college.

00:59:17.361 --> 00:59:19.860
And I was just wondering-- this
is kind of for both of you--

00:59:19.860 --> 00:59:21.870
how have you learned
from your identity

00:59:21.870 --> 00:59:25.650
being an athlete and the
things through practicing sport

00:59:25.650 --> 00:59:27.870
for your whole life
onto your career,

00:59:27.870 --> 00:59:30.240
and how has that shaped the
person that you are today,

00:59:30.240 --> 00:59:32.580
and the professional
decisions you've made?

00:59:32.580 --> 00:59:36.300
- For me, boxing
changed my life,

00:59:36.300 --> 00:59:39.064
because there's lots of moments
where you really have to--

00:59:39.064 --> 00:59:40.980
just being an athlete,
you've got to dig deep,

00:59:40.980 --> 00:59:42.979
and that's when you really
find out who you are.

00:59:42.979 --> 00:59:45.780
And naturally, as human beings,
we put limits on ourselves.

00:59:45.780 --> 00:59:47.400
We think, oh, we
can't go any further.

00:59:47.400 --> 00:59:48.870
I can't push any harder.

00:59:48.870 --> 00:59:51.330
And then you're in a situation
where you have to do it,

00:59:51.330 --> 00:59:53.127
and you're like, oh, I did it.

00:59:53.127 --> 00:59:55.710
And I remember that moment when
I thought that I couldn't, and

00:59:55.710 --> 00:59:58.126
then I remember that moment
when I found out that I could,

00:59:58.126 --> 01:00:01.640
and then now I can apply that
to everything else in my life.

01:00:01.640 --> 01:00:03.990
And any time that I just
think, this is too hard,

01:00:03.990 --> 01:00:05.040
I'm not going to
be able to do it.

01:00:05.040 --> 01:00:05.850
I'm like, what are
you talking about?

01:00:05.850 --> 01:00:06.960
Yes, you can.

01:00:06.960 --> 01:00:11.310
So that alone in itself is just
that confidence that I have

01:00:11.310 --> 01:00:12.670
that I've proven to myself.

01:00:12.670 --> 01:00:15.090
If I've proven to
myself one time,

01:00:15.090 --> 01:00:19.200
that means I can prove it to
myself a million more times.

01:00:19.200 --> 01:00:22.410
So that is just the
most basic thing

01:00:22.410 --> 01:00:25.410
I can tell you about
how being an athlete

01:00:25.410 --> 01:00:28.939
has just changed my life in
the way that I look at things.

01:00:28.939 --> 01:00:31.230
It doesn't mean that you're
not going to have failures.

01:00:31.230 --> 01:00:33.396
It doesn't mean that things
aren't going to be hard,

01:00:33.396 --> 01:00:35.814
but just having the
confidence and the self-belief

01:00:35.814 --> 01:00:37.230
to know that I can
pretty much get

01:00:37.230 --> 01:00:38.970
through just about anything.

01:00:38.970 --> 01:00:40.960
And I think that
that is so important.

01:00:40.960 --> 01:00:42.570
People need confidence
more than ever.

01:00:42.570 --> 01:00:44.340
So many people have
good ideas and things

01:00:44.340 --> 01:00:46.465
that they want to do, but
the fear holds them back.

01:00:49.830 --> 01:00:53.754
Like I said, I can't speak
to how sports really--

01:00:53.754 --> 01:00:55.920
I mean, the women that I
know that are athletes just

01:00:55.920 --> 01:00:57.517
have this level of confidence.

01:00:57.517 --> 01:00:58.350
You can just see it.

01:00:58.350 --> 01:00:58.920
You can fill it.

01:00:58.920 --> 01:00:59.586
You can hear it.

01:00:59.586 --> 01:01:01.914
And they can apply it.

01:01:01.914 --> 01:01:03.330
- Well, and you
think about this--

01:01:03.330 --> 01:01:07.350
for generations in this country,
we were not allowing 50 or 51%

01:01:07.350 --> 01:01:09.630
of our population to
learn these life lessons.

01:01:09.630 --> 01:01:11.610
What were we thinking?

01:01:11.610 --> 01:01:13.980
Again, Title IX, signed by
Richard Nixon, of all people,

01:01:13.980 --> 01:01:15.950
in June of 1972.

01:01:15.950 --> 01:01:19.620
- But I graduated from high
school in '76, so I was

01:01:19.620 --> 01:01:23.490
starting high school in '72,
and so I really saw almost none

01:01:23.490 --> 01:01:24.060
of it.

01:01:24.060 --> 01:01:25.686
Grew up in the suburbs
of Toledo, Ohio,

01:01:25.686 --> 01:01:27.560
and I was a six-sport
athlete in high school.

01:01:27.560 --> 01:01:29.400
And now you think, oh
she's a great athlete.

01:01:29.400 --> 01:01:30.210
No.

01:01:30.210 --> 01:01:33.600
I was good enough, and I'm
tall, and so I was able to play,

01:01:33.600 --> 01:01:34.860
and I was coordinated.

01:01:34.860 --> 01:01:36.870
But no one cared
about girls sports.

01:01:36.870 --> 01:01:40.170
Even my dad, who was my own
personal Title IX playing

01:01:40.170 --> 01:01:42.850
baseball with me when
I was growing up.

01:01:42.850 --> 01:01:44.730
But no one cared enough
about girls sports

01:01:44.730 --> 01:01:46.510
to want us to specialize.

01:01:46.510 --> 01:01:50.130
So I literally ran from first
doubles on the tennis court,

01:01:50.130 --> 01:01:52.980
to the field hockey match where
I was the captain of the team,

01:01:52.980 --> 01:01:54.120
and then basketball
and volleyball

01:01:54.120 --> 01:01:56.286
in the winter, and then
softball and track and field

01:01:56.286 --> 01:01:56.970
in the spring.

01:01:56.970 --> 01:01:59.940
- In my high school, 100%
of the kids went to college,

01:01:59.940 --> 01:02:02.400
and every mom and dad
wanted their daughter

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:06.360
to be a doctor or a lawyer, just
like their son, except sports.

01:02:06.360 --> 01:02:08.910
To show how ingrained
this was, no one

01:02:08.910 --> 01:02:11.250
even thought that we were
mowing the field hockey

01:02:11.250 --> 01:02:14.190
field while our
opponent was showing up.

01:02:14.190 --> 01:02:16.987
This was a Tuesday, where
the football field--

01:02:16.987 --> 01:02:17.820
what would that be--

01:02:17.820 --> 01:02:21.730
72 hours away was already
in pristine shape.

01:02:21.730 --> 01:02:23.110
And yet the field
hockey team was

01:02:23.110 --> 01:02:25.390
the one that was sending
kids onto college

01:02:25.390 --> 01:02:27.970
and winning Ohio
State championships,

01:02:27.970 --> 01:02:29.179
my high school did.

01:02:29.179 --> 01:02:30.970
And the football team
has had like two boys

01:02:30.970 --> 01:02:35.650
be kickers in college, which is
great, but it was so ingrained.

01:02:35.650 --> 01:02:37.942
And so for me, in addition
to just the pure love of all

01:02:37.942 --> 01:02:40.274
those sports, and to this day
I play sports and love it,

01:02:40.274 --> 01:02:42.760
and it's just a lifetime thing,
as I'm sure for most of you

01:02:42.760 --> 01:02:43.760
in this room.

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:47.650
But I also think, for me, it
has informed every ounce of what

01:02:47.650 --> 01:02:49.720
I do as a journalist
because I know what

01:02:49.720 --> 01:02:51.790
it was like to have
it myself because

01:02:51.790 --> 01:02:53.920
of my parents
encouraging it at a time

01:02:53.920 --> 01:02:56.800
when no one else was encouraging
their daughter to play sports.

01:02:56.800 --> 01:03:00.670
And so I had that, but
most women my age--

01:03:00.670 --> 01:03:03.850
and so to fight for Title
IX, to write those columns,

01:03:03.850 --> 01:03:07.390
to ask the questions as I
just did at Augusta National

01:03:07.390 --> 01:03:09.340
about Donald Trump and women.

01:03:09.340 --> 01:03:11.352
I will absolutely do that.

01:03:11.352 --> 01:03:12.060
Yeah, look it up.

01:03:12.060 --> 01:03:13.870
You might your
computer might explode.

01:03:16.910 --> 01:03:21.260
- And I'm going back
tonight to drive them crazy.

01:03:21.260 --> 01:03:24.790
But anyway, but bottom line
is that as a journalist having

01:03:24.790 --> 01:03:26.855
seen this incredible
change, it's fantastic.

01:03:26.855 --> 01:03:28.480
And it makes me smile,
and brings tears

01:03:28.480 --> 01:03:30.490
to my eyes to see
what girls have now,

01:03:30.490 --> 01:03:33.010
and how wonderful the change
has been in a blink of an eye

01:03:33.010 --> 01:03:35.080
in our nation's history.

01:03:35.080 --> 01:03:37.990
Thank you for your question.

01:03:37.990 --> 01:03:39.400
- Hello, my name
is Amanda Ortiz,

01:03:39.400 --> 01:03:43.630
and I'm a student athlete at
University of Massachusetts.

01:03:43.630 --> 01:03:46.420
My question was
regarding the inequality

01:03:46.420 --> 01:03:49.450
of women professional
athletes, and I

01:03:49.450 --> 01:03:53.560
guess regarding basketball
and soccer, relatively.

01:03:53.560 --> 01:03:56.720
Your thoughts and personal
experiences on that.

01:03:56.720 --> 01:04:00.730
- I don't have any personal
experience with it.

01:04:00.730 --> 01:04:04.840
I know that the Women's Sports
Foundation does a lot of work

01:04:04.840 --> 01:04:07.480
with collegiate sports
and trying to make sure

01:04:07.480 --> 01:04:11.560
that the playing field
is leveled as far as just

01:04:11.560 --> 01:04:13.990
dollars that are
allocated to the girls

01:04:13.990 --> 01:04:18.891
so that we have the same amount
opportunities as the boys'

01:04:18.891 --> 01:04:19.390
teams do.

01:04:19.390 --> 01:04:20.590
Do you have anything?

01:04:20.590 --> 01:04:25.540
- Yeah, and think we can
declare victory with Title IX

01:04:25.540 --> 01:04:29.126
because of the participation
piece of it where literally

01:04:29.126 --> 01:04:31.000
if a girl-- if you see
a girl in the airport,

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:32.335
what sport do you play?

01:04:32.335 --> 01:04:35.080
You never would have asked
that question 40 years ago.

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:37.120
So we've done so
many good things.

01:04:37.120 --> 01:04:38.890
Obviously the
under-served areas,

01:04:38.890 --> 01:04:41.120
and women coaching women
is where we're really--

01:04:41.120 --> 01:04:44.890
and Mary Jo Kane has done a lot
on this, and the Tucker Center,

01:04:44.890 --> 01:04:46.840
you guys do amazing work.

01:04:46.840 --> 01:04:48.872
So there's a lot
to go on that side.

01:04:48.872 --> 01:04:49.580
So it's not all--

01:04:49.580 --> 01:04:51.950
I said declare victory
because I want to be positive,

01:04:51.950 --> 01:04:53.200
but there's a lot to do there.

01:04:53.200 --> 01:04:55.630
The professional
side-- in some ways,

01:04:55.630 --> 01:04:59.650
of course, that's business, and
if people want to pay for it.

01:04:59.650 --> 01:05:02.320
So while I think the WNBA
is great and, for example,

01:05:02.320 --> 01:05:04.870
in DC where Elena Delle Donne
has now come to Washington,

01:05:04.870 --> 01:05:07.480
that is going to be a very
big deal in Washington.

01:05:07.480 --> 01:05:09.730
And the Mystics
will do very well.

01:05:09.730 --> 01:05:12.330
But the Wizards are so
entrenched, of course,

01:05:12.330 --> 01:05:14.080
they're not going to
overtake the Wizards.

01:05:14.080 --> 01:05:16.570
That would be
ridiculous to say that.

01:05:16.570 --> 01:05:18.280
And that's OK.

01:05:18.280 --> 01:05:20.124
I think my-- and we
want to make sure--

01:05:20.124 --> 01:05:21.040
we have a few minutes.

01:05:21.040 --> 01:05:23.837
Want to make sure to get to
as many questions as possible.

01:05:23.837 --> 01:05:25.670
Books are written on
this topic, and Mary Jo

01:05:25.670 --> 01:05:27.430
would be a great one
to talk to, but I

01:05:27.430 --> 01:05:32.380
do think that we judge women's
sports by the male model.

01:05:32.380 --> 01:05:34.960
And if you listen to shock
jock screaming radio, like,

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:38.000
oh WNBA isn't any good and
whatever-- well, you know what?

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:41.200
Could we start baseball today
if there was no baseball?

01:05:41.200 --> 01:05:42.130
Of course not.

01:05:42.130 --> 01:05:44.785
A sport that never existed
and now corporations

01:05:44.785 --> 01:05:46.660
are going to build
stadiums to have baseball?

01:05:46.660 --> 01:05:47.290
No.

01:05:47.290 --> 01:05:50.170
So the bottom line
is women's sports

01:05:50.170 --> 01:05:53.980
are coming into a chock
full calendar of sports,

01:05:53.980 --> 01:05:56.410
and I think they're doing great.

01:05:56.410 --> 01:05:58.450
And in 100 years,
we'll be equal?

01:05:58.450 --> 01:06:01.534
Probably not, but maybe.

01:06:01.534 --> 01:06:03.200
But there's also
things like gymnastics,

01:06:03.200 --> 01:06:04.150
where the women are the stars.

01:06:04.150 --> 01:06:05.858
Figure skating where
women are the stars.

01:06:05.858 --> 01:06:08.680
Soccer where our women's
team is certainly much more

01:06:08.680 --> 01:06:10.840
successful than our men's team.

01:06:10.840 --> 01:06:11.892
On and on it goes.

01:06:11.892 --> 01:06:13.850
And I think, again, you
look for those moments,

01:06:13.850 --> 01:06:16.182
but there's a lot on
that topic and feel free

01:06:16.182 --> 01:06:18.140
to shoot me an email if
you want at my website.

01:06:18.140 --> 01:06:19.750
I'm happy to discuss
it further with you.

01:06:19.750 --> 01:06:20.250
- Thank you.

01:06:20.250 --> 01:06:21.590
- Thank you.

01:06:21.590 --> 01:06:24.790
- I am Sharon Turbin,
I'm a sports psychologist

01:06:24.790 --> 01:06:29.020
in the area, and I could go
off in 10 different directions

01:06:29.020 --> 01:06:31.780
on some things that
you've said, Laila.

01:06:31.780 --> 01:06:36.520
One is that you were a
late initiator in terms

01:06:36.520 --> 01:06:38.860
of becoming an athlete
in your own mind,

01:06:38.860 --> 01:06:41.560
and I think there is an
upside to that, which

01:06:41.560 --> 01:06:43.480
is you weren't
necessarily shaped

01:06:43.480 --> 01:06:47.160
by that male model,
which you just described.

01:06:47.160 --> 01:06:53.020
And as women internalize the
values of sport that are still

01:06:53.020 --> 01:06:56.250
getting communicated
primarily by male coaching,

01:06:56.250 --> 01:07:01.480
there is a humanity about you,
and the fact that you started

01:07:01.480 --> 01:07:06.310
later, you already had command
of lots of parts of yourself.

01:07:06.310 --> 01:07:09.570
And I think doing some--
you are a role model,

01:07:09.570 --> 01:07:13.240
so modeling that
initiation as an athlete

01:07:13.240 --> 01:07:15.610
can occur all
through the lifecycle

01:07:15.610 --> 01:07:19.060
is actually a pretty
big statement.

01:07:19.060 --> 01:07:23.020
I worked with a power
lifter who started at 50

01:07:23.020 --> 01:07:27.820
and competed at
the national level.

01:07:27.820 --> 01:07:29.620
Not age weighted.

01:07:29.620 --> 01:07:33.280
Like, she competed full
strength at 50 years old.

01:07:33.280 --> 01:07:36.730
It's pretty compelling for
people later in the life cycle

01:07:36.730 --> 01:07:39.280
to have models of
later initiation

01:07:39.280 --> 01:07:42.010
and not to be necessarily
apologetic about not having

01:07:42.010 --> 01:07:44.980
been an athlete in the
developmental years,

01:07:44.980 --> 01:07:48.430
and all of the upside
that that kids do get

01:07:48.430 --> 01:07:50.770
from being in the sports world.

01:07:50.770 --> 01:07:56.020
And then my other
question to you is do you

01:07:56.020 --> 01:07:57.460
speak to those groups--

01:07:57.460 --> 01:08:00.820
to women who potentially
haven't necessarily

01:08:00.820 --> 01:08:03.610
identified as an
athlete, but are looking

01:08:03.610 --> 01:08:05.730
for ways to do that
sort of midlife,

01:08:05.730 --> 01:08:08.410
or throughout the life cycle?

01:08:08.410 --> 01:08:10.530
- I haven't up until this point.

01:08:10.530 --> 01:08:12.530
No one's ever
asked me to either,

01:08:12.530 --> 01:08:17.540
but I think that for me
being that boxing is just

01:08:17.540 --> 01:08:20.450
so different than
other sports, I

01:08:20.450 --> 01:08:25.580
was able to get into it late
because of the level of women's

01:08:25.580 --> 01:08:27.659
boxing, or just
boxing in general.

01:08:27.659 --> 01:08:28.700
It's one of those sports.

01:08:28.700 --> 01:08:29.450
It's not organized.

01:08:29.450 --> 01:08:30.890
Anyone can be like,
I want to be a boxer,

01:08:30.890 --> 01:08:32.240
any would can say I
want to be a promoter.

01:08:32.240 --> 01:08:34.790
And I don't really like the
business side of boxing,

01:08:34.790 --> 01:08:36.950
but I always want to
put that in perspective,

01:08:36.950 --> 01:08:39.491
because I can't-- like now, I
wouldn't have been able to just

01:08:39.491 --> 01:08:40.790
get in and just start playing.

01:08:40.790 --> 01:08:43.700
I could, but I'm saying
like tennis or something

01:08:43.700 --> 01:08:46.110
like that because people
have-- their skill level

01:08:46.110 --> 01:08:49.443
is so much greater because
they started sooner.

01:08:49.443 --> 01:08:51.109
So I wouldn't have
been able to do that.

01:08:51.109 --> 01:08:53.600
And that's why I, like I
said, that I regret it.

01:08:53.600 --> 01:08:55.260
I'm not one of those people
who wants to go back and go,

01:08:55.260 --> 01:08:56.318
I don't care if
I'm 40, I'm going

01:08:56.318 --> 01:08:57.800
to start playing tennis now.

01:08:57.800 --> 01:08:59.420
You know, I'm just
like, I'm good.

01:08:59.420 --> 01:09:03.740
So I'm good, next lifetime.

01:09:03.740 --> 01:09:06.109
I'm all for people who want
to do that, though, but you

01:09:06.109 --> 01:09:07.859
definitely have to be
passionate about it,

01:09:07.859 --> 01:09:09.025
and you have to be prepared.

01:09:09.025 --> 01:09:11.060
I have other goals
and dreams that I

01:09:11.060 --> 01:09:12.560
want to attain
because people ask

01:09:12.560 --> 01:09:14.680
me now do I want to come
back and train fighters.

01:09:14.680 --> 01:09:16.430
Do I want to come back
and promote fights.

01:09:16.430 --> 01:09:18.080
I'm like, that's
not my interest.

01:09:18.080 --> 01:09:19.496
And that's not
something I'm going

01:09:19.496 --> 01:09:21.950
to apologize for either,
because the women's boxing

01:09:21.950 --> 01:09:23.540
community says,
well why don't you

01:09:23.540 --> 01:09:25.250
come back and do
more for us, and I'm

01:09:25.250 --> 01:09:27.979
like, that's not my passion.

01:09:27.979 --> 01:09:30.185
I have a passion
to really encourage

01:09:30.185 --> 01:09:32.810
people to be the best that they
can be in life, whether they're

01:09:32.810 --> 01:09:33.859
an athlete or not.

01:09:33.859 --> 01:09:36.950
I'm not going to just limit
myself to just boxing.

01:09:36.950 --> 01:09:38.840
If I can just help and
come in and get out--

01:09:38.840 --> 01:09:39.673
get in and get out--

01:09:39.673 --> 01:09:41.520
I can, but to answer
your question,

01:09:41.520 --> 01:09:42.770
I would be open to doing that.

01:09:42.770 --> 01:09:44.150
Any time that I
can say something

01:09:44.150 --> 01:09:46.399
that can help somebody else,
that's what I want to do.

01:09:46.399 --> 01:09:49.040
As far as what I'm
going to make my focus,

01:09:49.040 --> 01:09:51.109
that comes down to
what's in my heart,

01:09:51.109 --> 01:09:53.600
but definitely--
if you're asking me

01:09:53.600 --> 01:09:58.340
if I'd be interested to speak,
then yes, I would, definitely.

01:09:58.340 --> 01:09:59.180
So, thank you.

01:09:59.180 --> 01:10:01.040
- Thank you, and you know what?

01:10:01.040 --> 01:10:02.281
We're going to do--

01:10:02.281 --> 01:10:03.530
we're going to go to overtime.

01:10:03.530 --> 01:10:05.670
We are we're
actually out of time,

01:10:05.670 --> 01:10:07.880
but we're going to do a
lightning round where we're

